A. Data Integration Fixes

Canonical consolidation

capture OEWM canonical_id and alias bundles during ConceptNet aggregation;
propagate canonical IDs into the final particle schema;
merge alias lists per language; expose preferred lemma + alternates.

BabelNet enrichment keys

attempt lookups by ConceptNet URI ‚Üí OEWM canonical ID ‚Üí normalized lemma;
record enrichment provenance per relation (origin = conceptnet | babelnet).

Frequency priors

generalise OEWM frequency loader for EN/RO tables (accept optional files);
attach per-language prior to each particle (persist even when absent).

üèóÔ∏è Architecture Changes Implemented

1. Binary Hyperdimensional Vectors ‚úÖ COMPLETED
Julia Side (julia/hdc_server.jl):
# Convert continuous projection to binary
binary_hv = BitVector(undef, 20_000)
for i in 1:20_000
    binary_hv[i] = output[i] &gt;= 0.0  # Sign-based binarization
end

# Pack to bytes: 20,000 bits = 2,500 bytes
binary_bytes = reinterpret(UInt8, binary_hv.chunks)
write(stdout, binary_bytes)  # 2,500 bytes vs 160,000!
Rust Side (src/lib.rs, src/ffi/julia_hdc.rs):
// Changed from Vec&lt;f64&gt; to Vec&lt;u8&gt;
pub struct SemanticParticle {
    pub vector: Vec&lt;u8&gt;,  // 2,500 bytes (20,000 bits packed)
    // ...
}

// Read 2,500 bytes instead of 160,000
pub fn expand_to_20kd(&mut self, input_300d: &[f64]) -&gt; Result&lt;Vec&lt;u8&gt;&gt; {
    let mut output_bytes = vec![0u8; 2_500];
    std::io::Read::read_exact(&mut process.stdout, &mut output_bytes)?;
    Ok(output_bytes)
}
Theoretical Foundation:

HDC canonical representation: binary/bipolar (Kanerva, Plate, Gayler)
Operations (XOR, POPCNT, rotate) map directly to hardware
Hamming distance = cosine similarity (for normalized vectors)
20,000 bits sufficient for ~10,000 quasi-orthogonal vectors

References:

Kanerva: ‚ÄúHyperdimensional Computing‚Äù (Redwood Center)
Yu et al.: Modern HDC survey (arXiv)

